context: The earliest Tibetan historical texts identify the <b5_0>Zhang Zhung<b5_0/> culture as a people who migrated from <b6_0>the <a0_0>Amdo region<b6_0/><a0_0/> into what is now the region of Guge in <a1_0>western Tibet<a1_0/>. <a2_0>Zhang Zhung<a2_0/> is considered to be the original home of the <b7_0>Bön religion<b7_0/>. By the 1st century BCE, a neighboring kingdom arose in the <b9_0>Yarlung<b9_0/> valley, and the Yarlung king, <a3_0>Drigum Tsenpo<a3_0/>, attempted to remove the influence of the Zhang Zhung by expelling the Zhang's Bön priests from Yarlung. He was assassinated and Zhang Zhung continued its dominance of the region until it was annexed by <b8_0>Songtsen Gampo<b8_0/> in the 7th century. Prior to <a4_0>Songtsän Gampo<a4_0/>, the kings of Tibet were more mythological than factual, and there is insufficient evidence of their existence.
